		Kevin Lee"))) ("Eye tracker hopes to improve road safety" "<article><section class=\"page\"><p>An eye tracking system on show at Computex in Taipei, might be the answer to creating safer roads. It uses a small camera mounted on the dashboard to monitor the driver for unsafe actions.</p><p>A webcam positioned just above the steering wheel is aimed at the driver. UTechzone developed the software used by the system, which can detect blink frequency, the direction the driver is looking, and mobile phone usage. The system offers an audible alert when the driver is doing something he shouldn’t. It can even detect when the driver is drowsy and alert him. </p><p>The maker of the system is talking to car manufacturers about using the system, though they’re not saying which ones.</p></section></article>" "http://www.techhive.com/article/2040904/eye-tracker-hopes-to-improve-road-safety.html#tk.rss_all" (20912 50068) old 2 nil nil ((title nil "Eye tracker hopes to improve road safety") (description nil "
<article><section class=\"page\"><p>An eye tracking system on show at Computex in Taipei, might be the answer to creating safer roads. It uses a small camera mounted on the dashboard to monitor the driver for unsafe actions.</p><p>A webcam positioned just above the steering wheel is aimed at the driver. UTechzone developed the software used by the system, which can detect blink frequency, the direction the driver is looking, and mobile phone usage. The system offers an audible alert when the driver is doing something he shouldn’t. It can even detect when the driver is drowsy and alert him. </p><p>The maker of the system is talking to car manufacturers about using the system, though they’re not saying which ones.</p></section></article>") (link nil "http://www.techhive.com/article/2040904/eye-tracker-hopes-to-improve-road-safety.html#tk.rss_all") (media:thumbnail ((url . "http://zapt2.staticworld.net/images/article/2013/06/eye_tracking_drivers_th-100040699-small.jpg"))) (media:content ((url . "http://zapt2.staticworld.net/images/article/2013/06/eye_tracking_drivers_th-100040699-small.jpg"))) (pubDate nil "Thu, 06 Jun 2013 10:15:00 -0700") (author nil "
		Nick Barber"))) ("AT&T, other carriers accept orders for BlackBerry's Q10 smartphone" "<article><section class=\"page\"><p>BlackBerry’s Q10, the company’s new smartphone with a QWERTY keyboard, is finally appearing in U.S. retail channels. AT&amp;T is the latest carrier to start taking pre-orders for the phone.
</p><p>Orders for the Q10 on AT&amp;T <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ATT/status/342015451943030785\">began Wednesday</a>, with an expected shipping date of June 18. <a href=\"http://www.verizonwireless.com/b2c/store/controller?item=phoneFirst&amp;action=viewPhoneDetail&amp;selectedPhoneId=6785\">Like rival Verizon</a>, AT&amp;T charges $199.99 for the handset with a two-year agreement.
</p><p>Verizon <a href=\"https://news.verizonwireless.com/news/2013/05/blackberry-q10.html\">announced Wednesday</a> that it would start selling the Q10 online on June 6 and that the unit will be in its stores on June 10.
</p><p>T-Mobile sells the smartphones under its installment plan. You’ll pay $99.99 at time of purchase and $20 a month for 24 months. If you terminate service with the carrier during the two-year period, you’ll be tapped for the outstanding balance for the phone, which sells for $579.99.
